a pathologist's favorite image. And as you can imagine, this

461
00:26:45.620 --> 00:26:49.590
allows a kind of cross-training. But for today, what I

462
00:26:49.620 --> 00:26:53.530
wanted to show you is you can take exactly the same thing and you can now move this

463
00:26:53.580 --> 00:26:57.340
into three dimensions. But the trick in this case is not real

464
00:26:57.540 --> 00:27:01.390
H&amp;E, because real H&amp;E on a two-millimeter piece of tissue isn't going to work.

465
00:27:01.780 --> 00:27:05.500
Instead, this is what we call virtual H&amp;E. So it isn't as good as H&amp;E.

466
00:27:05.580 --> 00:27:07.220
You wouldn't go and do a diagnosis on it.

467
00:27:07.500 --> 00:27:10.880
But you can see that it actually gives you a great view of the tissue architecture.

468
00:27:11.240 --> 00:27:15.160
And it's computed using a more or less fancy method, directly

469
00:27:15.200 --> 00:27:17.200
out of autofluorescence and a nuclear stain.

470
00:27:17.509 --> 00:27:19.729
And again, this can be done on many microscopes.

471
00:27:20.060 --> 00:27:23.710
And so, just to give you a sense of what the application would be, slightly

472
00:27:23.720 --> 00:27:26.280
different color scheme here. Here's synthetic H&amp;E.

473
00:27:26.320 --> 00:27:29.920
You'll recognize these as colonic crypts here, and you can see the

474
00:27:29.960 --> 00:27:33.490
individual T cells. So you can take a cell type here, which we have only one color,

475
00:27:33.880 --> 00:27:37.490
and you can embed it into the full sort of complexity of that tissue.

476
00:27:37.960 --> 00:27:41.560
And as you hear more, you can then compute on those tissues and get all sorts of

477
00:27:41.600 --> 00:27:45.360
features. And in this case, we have sort of a boring one, which is the volume of

478
00:27:45.400 --> 00:27:47.840
individual crypts and whether they're undergoing fission events.

479
00:27:48.200 --> 00:27:52.020
So this type of technology, we think, actually is broadly scalable.

480
00:27:52.080 --> 00:27:53.440
I don't think any of these are diagnostic.

481
00:27:54.180 --> 00:27:56.420
But this actually can be done relatively inexpensively.

482
00:27:56.450 --> 00:27:59.990
And when you're done, you can re-embed and put it back on the shelf and come back

483
00:28:00.060 --> 00:28:02.860
to it some other day.

484
00:28:03.940 --> 00:28:07.630
So in conclusion, I hope I've shown you that this kind of profiling can have lots

485
00:28:07.680 --> 00:28:11.280
of variants, from what you might be familiar with, five-micron FAP

486
00:28:11.540 --> 00:28:15.100
frozen. You can integrate this in various ways with H&amp;E and

487
00:28:15.140 --> 00:28:19.009
transcriptomics. I've shown you a bunch of thick section imaging methods, and

488
00:28:19.040 --> 00:28:22.120
these can be implemented on a really wide range of different instruments.

489
00:28:22.140 --> 00:28:25.990
So one should think about this not as a specific technology I need to go and

490
00:28:26.040 --> 00:28:29.000
buy from vendor X, but just sort of a branch of

491
00:28:29.040 --> 00:28:32.860
histopathology or a branch of microscopy that's broadly

492
00:28:32.880 --> 00:28:33.460
applicable.

493
00:28:34.900 --> 00:28:37.760
And then finally, you could ask, should I do this for everything?

494
00:28:37.840 --> 00:28:41.540
So I think there's a certain hype around 3D tissue imaging,

495
00:28:41.860 --> 00:28:45.780
and the answer is clearly no. If you're going to do a large clinical cohort

496
00:28:45.860 --> 00:28:48.820
or a large mouse study, you're just not going to 3D image everything.

497
00:28:48.880 --> 00:28:52.730
And so the concept, still vague in our minds, you can imagine doing some of this

498
00:28:52.730 --> 00:28:56.540
with machine learning, goes back to a sort of stereology idea, is a

499
00:28:56.640 --> 00:29:00.340
limited amount of sampling in 3D gives you the capacity to

500
00:29:00.400 --> 00:29:02.700
understand 2D images much, much better.

501
00:29:03.289 --> 00:29:07.260
And we actually are learning that there are sort of shadows in a 2D image

502
00:29:07.300 --> 00:29:11.060
of a 3D structure that we couldn't appreciate without the 3D ground

503
00:29:11.080 --> 00:29:12.640
truth. So let me

504
00:29:13.720 --> 00:29:17.360
then close by sort of thanking-- I've tried to thank the

505
00:29:17.420 --> 00:29:20.260
funders first, but I also want to thank the instrument makers who've come along and

506
00:29:20.320 --> 00:29:22.270
helped us with this. So a lot of them have loaned us

507
00:29:23.480 --> 00:29:25.180
instruments we couldn't have afforded otherwise.

508
00:29:26.200 --> 00:29:29.240
And the methods that are here, if you're interested, are all public domain.

509
00:29:29.520 --> 00:29:33.230
And I think you could just apply them by going to your friendly, local,

510
00:29:33.500 --> 00:29:35.960
NIH-supported microscopy facility.

511
00:29:36.620 --> 00:29:39.440
I've tried to recognize the people who did this work, but I want to say it's been

512
00:29:39.460 --> 00:29:41.800
incredibly dependent on pathology collaborators.

513
00:29:41.820 --> 00:29:45.760
So our group's been really lucky to have been befriended by pathologists on

514
00:29:45.820 --> 00:29:48.880
several continents. And I want to call out particularly Sandro Santagata.

515
00:29:49.350 --> 00:29:53.190
And then finally, a software and data analysis team whose contributions I

516
00:29:53.240 --> 00:29:55.280
haven't fully recognized. Thank you very much.

517
00:30:03.460 --> 00:30:06.800
So what I'm going to do is I'm going to entertain five minutes of questions, and

518
00:30:06.840 --> 00:30:10.300
then we'll hear from Ashley, and then recall that we have an opportunity to come

519
00:30:10.320 --> 00:30:11.190
back at the end,

520
00:30:12.260 --> 00:30:14.760
and actually do a more extended Q&amp;A series.

521
00:30:14.840 --> 00:30:18.320
So, if there are any questions, please come up to the microphones.

522
00:30:20.760 --> 00:30:20.940
Great

523
00:30:21.920 --> 00:30:25.340
presentation. It's really exciting to see all these new techniques and what we can

524
00:30:25.380 --> 00:30:25.800
do now.

525
00:30:26.620 --> 00:30:29.160
And my question is kind of a curiosity.

526
00:30:29.700 --> 00:30:33.640
How it works for tissues with a lot of inflammation, like tumor,

527
00:30:33.940 --> 00:30:37.300
when you have a lot of destruction of the morphology,

528
00:30:38.060 --> 00:30:38.620
is these

529
00:30:39.480 --> 00:30:42.120
all techniques able to identify that?

530
00:30:42.680 --> 00:30:45.320
And also, what is your preferred method

531
00:30:45.400 --> 00:30:49.192
to... conserve the tissue, like PPFE,

532
00:30:49.572 --> 00:30:53.331
frozen tissue, and how that influence the background

533
00:30:53.652 --> 00:30:55.472
of the tissue, like the signal?

534
00:30:56.132 --> 00:30:57.972
Yeah. A couple of fantastic questions.

535
00:30:58.032 --> 00:30:58.152
So,

536
00:30:59.032 --> 00:31:02.792
one of them is one of the most interesting things in a tumor setting

537
00:31:02.912 --> 00:31:05.952
actually to look at is the structure of the

538
00:31:06.812 --> 00:31:09.552
necrotic and perinecrotic environment in an advanced tumor.

539
00:31:09.912 --> 00:31:13.312
That thing is just chock-a-block with cytokines, and so T cells.

540
00:31:13.352 --> 00:31:15.212
And it generally is filled with dead neutrophils.

541
00:31:15.272 --> 00:31:18.932
So that can actually be imaged very nicely using that synthetic

542
00:31:19.132 --> 00:31:21.492
H&amp;E I showed you. Antibodies won't stain it.

543
00:31:21.712 --> 00:31:23.712
Synthetic H&amp;E pulls it out beautifully.

544
00:31:24.392 --> 00:31:28.382
With respect to tissue preservation, again, it depends very much what's

545
00:31:28.652 --> 00:31:32.112
necessary there. So I think this 30-micron thick slice for

546
00:31:32.152 --> 00:31:34.972
any kind of research study is pretty good.

547
00:31:34.992 --> 00:31:37.402
You can usually, for a solid tumor, sacrifice that.

548
00:31:37.452 --> 00:31:40.872
It's less than what you sacrifice to do exome sequencing, by the way.

549
00:31:42.392 --> 00:31:45.892
But I think if you want to do that very thick light sheet, you sort of have to

550
00:31:45.932 --> 00:31:49.632
dedicate a specimen to that. So for the moment, I think in a research setting, it's

551
00:31:49.672 --> 00:31:53.592
best with things like colorectal cancer where sadly, by stage III, you

552
00:31:53.652 --> 00:31:56.822
have a lot of blocks. So, and then finally, you asked about frozen.

553
00:31:56.872 --> 00:31:58.712
We work with FFPE. Frozen works fine.

554
00:31:58.772 --> 00:32:01.882
Just remember, anytime you use frozen, the antibodies are different, the buffers

555
00:32:01.912 --> 00:32:03.582
are different, the concepts are the same.

556
00:32:06.892 --> 00:32:08.932
Okay, I think what we'll do is go on to Ashley's talk.

557
00:32:08.992 --> 00:32:12.472
So I'm very pleased to be able to introduce Dr.

558
00:32:12.552 --> 00:32:15.432
Keman, who's going to talk about AI approaches to 3D imaging.

559
00:32:15.572 --> 00:32:19.312
We'll entertain questions after hers, and then we'll go into an extended

560
00:32:19.812 --> 00:32:21.372
sort of discussion. And we have until

561
00:32:22.412 --> 00:32:23.472
2:00 for that. Thank

562
00:32:23.512 --> 00:32:27.432
you.

563
00:32:33.132 --> 00:32:34.912
Thank you all. My name is Ashley Keman.

564
00:32:34.952 --> 00:32:38.872
I'm a quantitative biologist at Johns Hopkins, and today what I'd

565
00:32:38.892 --> 00:32:42.712
like to focus on, now that we've had this nice talk about imaging, is

566
00:32:42.792 --> 00:32:46.722
how we can apply AI and analytic technologies to these images

567
00:32:46.732 --> 00:32:50.432
to quantify them. So what I'm going to do today is give a quick

568
00:32:50.632 --> 00:32:54.211
high-level sense of the types of imaging we do.

569
00:32:54.221 --> 00:32:58.152
When is 2D imaging ideal? How can we go beyond 2D, and

570
00:32:58.192 --> 00:33:02.022
what common methods do we apply? Which distinct advantages do

571
00:33:02.032 --> 00:33:04.972
things like intact imaging and sectioning-based imaging have?

572
00:33:05.832 --> 00:33:09.572
How AI has changed the game, the fact that a lot of these imaging methods date

573
00:33:09.612 --> 00:33:11.792
back as long ago as the 1850s,

574
00:33:12.752 --> 00:33:16.692
and why, in my opinion, it's AI and quantitative imaging that

575
00:33:16.892 --> 00:33:19.132
has made this the booming field that it is today.

576
00:33:19.972 --> 00:33:23.912
And then I'll talk about specific applications of AI, which models we use, and

577
00:33:24.012 --> 00:33:24.972
with what applications.

578
00:33:26.312 --> 00:33:30.152
So just to begin with, to talk a bit about what is 2D

579
00:33:30.212 --> 00:33:32.412
imaging, how is it used, what benefits does it have?

580
00:33:33.472 --> 00:33:37.352
2D imaging, it's the foundation of today's anatomic pathology in the

581
00:33:37.412 --> 00:33:39.492
clinic. It's how patients typically get diagnosed.

582
00:33:40.292 --> 00:33:43.952
The most common stain that you'll see is hematoxylin and eosin, H&amp;E,

583
00:33:44.472 --> 00:33:46.712
which uses simple pH to stain

584
00:33:47.912 --> 00:33:51.812
the nuclei cytoplasm collagen

585
00:33:51.912 --> 00:33:52.532
in tissues.

586
00:33:53.632 --> 00:33:57.372
Today, we use a lot of advanced imaging on top of this, things like cyclic

587
00:33:57.452 --> 00:34:00.032
IF to do highplex imaging, multi-omics.

588
00:34:01.012 --> 00:34:04.452
All of this can be done in 2D, and one of the biggest benefits of

589
00:34:04.612 --> 00:34:07.532
2D is that we can analyze big data sets.

590
00:34:07.572 --> 00:34:11.232
So if the question you have needs many, many patients, tens to thousands of

591
00:34:11.272 --> 00:34:13.892
patients, typically 2D is the way to go.

592
00:34:15.632 --> 00:34:19.192
On the second hand, if the question you have has to do with connectivity, has to do

593
00:34:19.232 --> 00:34:23.092
with how cells communicate and something like 2D, say, is going to

594
00:34:23.272 --> 00:34:24.832
cut the body of a cell, is going to

595
00:34:25.993 --> 00:34:29.372
not sample what you need, that might be a time when 2D is

596
00:34:29.432 --> 00:34:32.973
insufficient. We have two main technologies used in the field.

597
00:34:33.102 --> 00:34:36.852
One is sectioning based. That's what my team uses a lot is histological

598
00:34:36.932 --> 00:34:38.872
sectioning going all the way down a clinical block.

599
00:34:39.412 --> 00:34:43.292
You also have intact imaging, things like CT, quantitative

600
00:34:43.332 --> 00:34:45.132
phase imaging, light sheet imaging,

601
00:34:46.053 --> 00:34:49.212
each of those with its own distinct advantages that I'll get into.

602
00:34:49.272 --> 00:34:53.042
While these have benefits, they also have downsides, the biggest of which is it can

603
00:34:53.072 --> 00:34:56.493
be tedious and expensive to collect this data, so it's

604
00:34:56.553 --> 00:35:00.072
infeasible to think of studies on the scale of thousands of tissues.

605
00:35:00.292 --> 00:35:02.652
This is something that you might look at tens of patients,

606
00:35:03.832 --> 00:35:06.421
to look distinctly and deeply into individual samples.

607
00:35:07.992 --> 00:35:11.512
So just a quick visual sense of what's done today in the clinic.

608
00:35:12.472 --> 00:35:16.272
And I want to give a quick defense of 2D pathology because as

609
00:35:16.332 --> 00:35:20.272
decades of diagnostic anatomic pathology have shown, it

610
00:35:20.312 --> 00:35:24.212
can be quite effective. It allows pathologists to diagnose patients, to

611
00:35:24.272 --> 00:35:28.232
stage patients, and to see actually a lot about the

612
00:35:28.252 --> 00:35:32.212
TME in tissues. So, in the clinic, what's done if tissue

613
00:35:32.232 --> 00:35:35.892
is excised, is that tissue will be cut into many small

614
00:35:35.932 --> 00:35:39.612
pieces, put into individual FFPE wax blocks,

615
00:35:40.312 --> 00:35:43.392
and individual 2D sections will be cut off of each of those blocks.

616
00:35:43.592 --> 00:35:44.752
A pathologist will look

617
00:35:46.012 --> 00:35:49.652
at each of those blocks independently, so it's a misconception that 2D

618
00:35:49.712 --> 00:35:51.532
pathology means looking at one slide.

619
00:35:51.612 --> 00:35:54.952
Pathologists typically look at many slides, just not

620
00:35:54.972 --> 00:35:55.652
continuous.

621
00:35:56.492 --> 00:35:58.652
They'll typically use H&amp;E and will use

622
00:35:59.772 --> 00:36:03.732
isolated immunolabeling, IHC, if in a specific diagnosis

623
00:36:03.792 --> 00:36:06.981
it's needed. So in some diseases, they use Ki67.

624
00:36:07.032 --> 00:36:10.992
In some diseases, they use things like ECAD, CK19 to

625
00:36:11.032 --> 00:36:11.972
subtype diseases.

626
00:36:12.992 --> 00:36:14.022
So 2D is

627
00:36:15.032 --> 00:36:18.732
good at looking at multiple locations in a block, but it's not so good at

628
00:36:18.792 --> 00:36:22.532
connectivity. So maybe, on one section, you

629
00:36:22.592 --> 00:36:25.692
see what looks like two bodies, but on the second section, you would see that they

630
00:36:25.752 --> 00:36:28.611
combine, and it's the same cell. 2D is not going to get you that.

631
00:36:30.252 --> 00:36:34.172
On the second hand, we have technologies like CODA used by my team, which

632
00:36:34.232 --> 00:36:34.592
uses

633
00:36:35.572 --> 00:36:39.552
consecutive H&amp;E sections. This allows us to image a volume of

634
00:36:39.572 --> 00:36:41.672
tissue instead of individual 2D slices.

635
00:36:42.272 --> 00:36:44.392
The upside is that now we have connectivity.

636
00:36:45.312 --> 00:36:49.272
We can see spatial association between tissues quite well, but you can

637
00:36:49.312 --> 00:36:53.284
imagine the downside that if we pickblock K and block A, B,

638
00:36:53.364 --> 00:36:57.193
and C had the diagnostic entity, we'll miss it because we only

639
00:36:57.284 --> 00:37:01.084
focus on one specific location within a block, even though we can deeply analyze

640
00:37:01.104 --> 00:37:01.724
that location.

641
00:37:04.684 --> 00:37:07.304
So just to sum it up, when is 2D imaging useful?

642
00:37:07.444 --> 00:37:10.864
Again, in the clinic, it's been shown that it's quite useful, although people have

643
00:37:10.904 --> 00:37:14.824
been publishing individual examples of when, even in the clinic, 2D imaging

644
00:37:14.844 --> 00:37:18.814
can fail. 2D is also quite useful, again, when you want to look

645
00:37:18.844 --> 00:37:22.584
at many patients. So looking maybe deep within a patient to ask a specific question

646
00:37:22.644 --> 00:37:25.184
might not be as helpful as looking at many patients.

647
00:37:26.084 --> 00:37:29.624
And finally, when someone has applications that they want to apply

648
00:37:29.664 --> 00:37:33.644
multi-omics assays, things like Visium, things like highplex IF

649
00:37:33.724 --> 00:37:34.104
staining,

650
00:37:35.404 --> 00:37:38.944
it can be quite expensive to apply this to multiple sections, so oftentimes,

651
00:37:39.004 --> 00:37:42.444
depending on the question, it might be best to apply it to many patients as opposed

652
00:37:42.454 --> 00:37:43.684
to many sections of the same.

653
00:37:45.384 --> 00:37:49.044
And now I'll give a few examples of when 2D may not be sufficient.

654
00:37:49.924 --> 00:37:53.464
This example is looking at cyclic IF staining in TMAs.

655
00:37:53.544 --> 00:37:55.724
So a TMA is a plug of a

656
00:37:56.964 --> 00:38:00.644
block of human tissue, and on a single slide you might have two dozens patients'

657
00:38:00.664 --> 00:38:01.244
tissue,

658
00:38:02.164 --> 00:38:05.604
all laid on the same tissue block. So with each section you can sample tens of

659
00:38:05.624 --> 00:38:06.044
patients.

660
00:38:07.024 --> 00:38:11.004
The downside of a TMA is to be able to fit so many patients' tissue on a slide, you

661
00:38:11.024 --> 00:38:13.504
have to cut a small piece of each block.

662
00:38:14.864 --> 00:38:18.744
So in this study, Lin et al showed quite nicely that depending on

663
00:38:18.844 --> 00:38:19.864
what you quantify

664
00:38:21.504 --> 00:38:25.484
in these images, something like a TMA is insufficient

665
00:38:25.524 --> 00:38:28.754
to ask the question of how inflamed is this specific sample?

666
00:38:29.544 --> 00:38:33.324
Maybe you could ask the question if you look at tens and tens of samples, how

667
00:38:33.364 --> 00:38:36.044
inflamed is colon tissue typically?

668
00:38:36.064 --> 00:38:39.944
But you cannot ask how inflamed is this patient's colon, because as you look

669
00:38:39.964 --> 00:38:43.604
down multiple sections of the same block of tissue, that inflammation can

670
00:38:43.664 --> 00:38:47.444
change wildly. Between slide to slide, you might have five times as

671
00:38:47.484 --> 00:38:49.484
many immune cells as you go down.

672
00:38:51.584 --> 00:38:55.544
To give a second example of when 2D pathology may be insufficient,

673
00:38:55.904 --> 00:38:57.464
we can think about collagen alignment.

674
00:38:58.104 --> 00:39:01.844
So if you look at the video on the left side of the slide, the blue label

675
00:39:01.984 --> 00:39:05.524
is showing you ductal epithelium, and the pink is showing you

676
00:39:05.584 --> 00:39:06.043
collagen.

677
00:39:06.904 --> 00:39:10.624
And this video is made of thousands of consecutive H&amp;E

678
00:39:10.664 --> 00:39:13.704
slides with an AI model applied to them to label cell types.

679
00:39:14.604 --> 00:39:18.584
And each one of these sections, we can pull out individually and look at

680
00:39:18.604 --> 00:39:20.744
what the pathologist would've seen if they saw this slide.

681
00:39:21.204 --> 00:39:25.013
And you can imagine, if we go in and we pull out the slide that the duct was

682
00:39:25.024 --> 00:39:28.264
cut axially, we can see one angle of that duct.

683
00:39:28.804 --> 00:39:32.344
And if we go down about 10 sections, we can catch a slide that the duct was cut

684
00:39:32.444 --> 00:39:34.264
longitudinally along its long axis.

685
00:39:35.064 --> 00:39:38.944
And then we can quantify on each of these images, how well-aligned

686
00:39:38.964 --> 00:39:42.844
does the collagen look. And we did this, and we showed that, in fact,

687
00:39:42.964 --> 00:39:46.784
the collagen encasing this duct, this blue tube, is

688
00:39:46.864 --> 00:39:50.684
highly aligned. But if you catch the axially

689
00:39:50.744 --> 00:39:54.004
sectioned duct, which is the most likely angle to cut this duct at,

690
00:39:54.784 --> 00:39:57.323
it does not look aligned. And if you quantified that, you would come to the

691
00:39:57.364 --> 00:39:59.364
conclusion that this collagen is not aligned.

692
00:39:59.924 --> 00:40:03.564
So this is an instance in which 2D pathology is going to give you inconsistent

693
00:40:03.584 --> 00:40:05.744
data, depending on the angle of sectioning that you catch.

694
00:40:07.784 --> 00:40:11.264
The next example I want to give is one that specifically has impact in the clinic.

695
00:40:12.664 --> 00:40:16.284
When pathologists diagnose needle biopsies, tiny

696
00:40:16.804 --> 00:40:18.424
plugs of tissue taken out of patients,

697
00:40:20.304 --> 00:40:23.774
a tiny amount of tissue is taken, and even less of that tissue is used

698
00:40:23.804 --> 00:40:27.484
diagnostically. Pathologists will look at maybe one 2D slice of that needle

699
00:40:27.544 --> 00:40:28.004
biopsy.

700
00:40:28.804 --> 00:40:30.804
And what this team did is they

701
00:40:32.924 --> 00:40:36.424
applied open top light sheet imaging to an intact needle biopsy.

702
00:40:36.684 --> 00:40:40.484
And then by looking section by section, they showed each of those synthetic H&amp;E

