00:40:40.544 --> 00:40:44.404
slides to a pathologist and asked them to assign

704
00:40:44.504 --> 00:40:46.484
the Gleason staging slide by slide.

705
00:40:47.244 --> 00:40:51.064
And they showed that even within a tiny needle biopsy, depending on

706
00:40:51.104 --> 00:40:54.084
which section the pathologist looks at in the clinic, the outcome would change.

707
00:40:56.064 --> 00:40:59.744
Which is significant because, say, if a patient is assigned a Gleason 9,

708
00:41:01.144 --> 00:41:04.804
the action, the actional output is going to

709
00:41:04.844 --> 00:41:06.864
change as opposed to if it was, say, a Gleason 5.

710
00:41:07.724 --> 00:41:11.534
So this shows that in some cases, a 2D H&amp;E

711
00:41:11.624 --> 00:41:14.884
slide in the clinic is not enough to make an actionable decision.

712
00:41:16.664 --> 00:41:19.904
And then finally, I want to show an additional example using H&amp;E imaging.

713
00:41:20.564 --> 00:41:24.504
In this case, the video that you see on the left is a whole human fallopian tube,

