00:42:21.904 --> 00:42:25.894
How likely is the SEFIM technique to catch these STIC lesions that we could

731
00:42:25.964 --> 00:42:26.484
find

732
00:42:27.484 --> 00:42:30.304
in this automated mapping? And we found that

733
00:42:31.204 --> 00:42:35.024
the 2D sampling of the fallopian tube exactly

734
00:42:35.084 --> 00:42:37.724
explains the fact that we miss these lesions in the clinic.

735
00:42:38.744 --> 00:42:42.354
Not to say that in the clinic, they should be exhaustively sectioning tubes because

736
00:42:42.384 --> 00:42:46.204
the goal of the clinic is not to find these small indolent

737
00:42:46.264 --> 00:42:49.684
lesions, it's to identify the active STIC lesions that can become invasive.

738
00:42:50.504 --> 00:42:54.304
But the point that we make with this is that you cannot use the same

739
00:42:54.344 --> 00:42:58.104
methods to diagnose patients as to come up with these incidences,

740
00:42:59.104 --> 00:43:02.484
because what we show is 2D is insufficient to find all the STICs.

741
00:43:02.524 --> 00:43:04.654
In fact, it's likely that all healthy women

742
00:43:05.624 --> 00:43:09.292
have these indolent STIC lesions.And that methods such as

743
00:43:09.492 --> 00:43:12.932
this exhaustive mapping may be needed to come up with those estimations.

744
00:43:16.752 --> 00:43:20.622
Okay, so I want to now talk about the types of imaging we use and then

